  "prompt": "How do deaf people communicate?",
  "response": "Deaf people communicate using a variety of methods, depending on individual preferences, cultural background, and the degree of hearing loss. Some common forms of communication include:\n\n1. **Sign Languages**: \n   - Sign languages, such as American Sign Language (ASL), British Sign Language (BSL), and many others, are fully developed natural languages that use hand shapes, facial expressions, and body movements to convey meaning. These languages have their own grammar and syntax and can express complex concepts just as spoken languages do.\n\n2. **Lip Reading**:\n   - Some deaf individuals can read lips to understand spoken language by watching the speaker\u2019s mouth movements, facial expressions, and body language. This method can be challenging and often requires careful attention and context.\n\n3. **Written Communication**:\n   - Writing notes, using text messages, emails, or other written forms of communication can be effective, especially in environments where sign language isn\u2019t feasible or where the interaction is brief.\n\n4. **Speech and Residual Hearing**:\n   - Some deaf people use hearing aids or cochlear implants to enhance their residual hearing and may use spoken language as their primary mode of communication, often with the aid of speech therapy to improve articulation and comprehension.\n\n5. **Technology**:\n   - Various technologies aid communication, such as video relay services (VRS), real-time text (RTT), and apps designed for deaf and hard of hearing individuals. Video relay services allow users to communicate with hearing individuals using a sign language interpreter through video calls.\n\n6. **Finger Spelling**:\n   - Finger spelling is a part of many sign languages where each letter of a word is spelled out using specific hand shapes. It is often used for proper nouns or technical terms that do not have a sign language equivalent.\n\n7. **Gestures and Body Language**:\n   - Informal gestures and body language can also be used to convey meaning, especially in casual or immediate situations.\n\nIt\u2019s important to recognize and respect the preferred communication method of each individual, as there is significant diversity within the deaf community regarding how people choose to communicate.",
